Health Minister, Dr Zweli Mkhize says there's evidence that masks can protect against COVID-19. Courtesy #DStv403 JOHANNESBURG - Health Minister, Dr Zweli Mkhize says there's evidence that masks can protect against COVID-19. Mkhize said people who wear masks should take precautions. COVID-19: Mkhize says face masks are essential People should avoid touching the mask and should wash the mask frequently. Mkhize said people could use cloth masks as long as it had enough layers. WATCH: Mkhize briefs media on meeting with private health sector He added that going forward, people may be required to wear masks in overcrowded places. The number of COVID-19 related deaths in South Africa has risen to 24. The number of confirmed coronavirus cases in South Africa is 2,003. The Department of Health encourages South Africans to wear facemasks to mitigate COVID-19. The Department of Health encourages South Africans to wear facemasks to mitigate COVID-19. The Department of Health encourages South Africans to wear facemasks to mitigate COVID-19. The Department of Health encourages South Africans to wear facemasks to mitigate COVID-19. - Coronavirus Hotline Number: 0800 029 999 from 8am to 4pm, Monday to Friday Help protect your loved ones by sharing this official South African government COVID-19 service with your family, friends and community. Send HI to 0600 123 456 on WhatsApp. The NICD has another Clinician Hotline to improve #COVID19 communication and support for healthcare providers. The Clinician Hotline is 0800 11 1131, operating 24 hrs. The Public Hotline is 0800 029 999 also operating 24hrs.